availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: Black (0120830) gives this as a form of 'àite' but doesn't quite know what to make of it. Could it be a form of aiteamh as noted here?

WGI, RB gives the verbs "teirig" and "tàirr" as two different verbs in the HDSG slips. I would have given both verbs the OIr HW of "do-airicc" (http://www.dil.ie/17140) but have split them up into "do-airicc" goes to "teirig" and "do-airret" goes to "tàirr". Is that right or not?

The digitised HDSG Collection of Slips comsists of the slips Ronald Black made for the HDSG and for himself. As is evident from this edition, the MS is damaged at this point. The digital slip (0120694) gives the headword slabhra and the quotation is ríoghsh[labhra] but the it is written in the Notes section that no dictionary slip was made out [and thus the] reading [is] conjectural.

WGI, 'as', a form of 'is' or 'os' for 'ós'? I think this is an 'a' based on the 'ainm' two lines previous as the penstroke appears to curve downwards the right as he does with his 'a's do but EPT has suggested 'os'.

The letter preceding the d is strange and I am not quite sure what to make of it. It appears to have iniditally been a character, now illegible, which was subsequently changed. The 'corrected' reading may be intended to be 'ui'
Black (0121092) created a slip for this point of the MS with the headword tairmeasgadh but no dictionary slip. There is no further information given in this slip.
The lenition marker is placed over the final t in this word but has been transcribed as belonging to the c and consequently the -cht to indicate pre-aspiration.
Black (0002490) gives the headword gá here.
Black (0002347) gives the headword dám here.
There are three HDG slips for this, Black (0080817), (0130543), and (0110588\).
WGI, EPT suggested we emend to "parais" for sense but I subsequently read Black's slip which notes or read read pásaisi for alliteration. Which do you think is best?
Black supplies the -in in the HDSG slip for "gath": (0002485).
